  "local_port": 56248,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I am 28 years old with 4 years banking experience. What government jobs in India can I apply for?",
  "response": "With 4 years of banking experience and at the age of 28, you are eligible for a variety of government jobs in India. Your banking experience can be a valuable asset, especially for roles in finance, administration, and related fields. Here are some government job options you can consider:\n\n### 1. **Banking and Finance Roles**\n   - **Public Sector Banks (PSBs):**\n     - Probationary Officer (PO) through IBPS PO exam.\n     - Specialist Officer (SO) in areas like IT, HR, Law, etc., through IBPS SO exam.\n   - **RBI (Reserve Bank of India):**\n     - RBI Grade B Officer: For managerial roles in RBI.\n     - Assistant: For clerical/assistant roles in RBI.\n   - **NABARD (National Bank for Agriculture and Rural Development):**\n     - Grade A and Grade B Officers: For roles related to rural development and agriculture finance.\n   - **SEBI (Securities and Exchange Board of India):**\n     - Officer Grade A (Assistant Manager): For regulatory and supervisory roles.\n\n### 2. **Civil Services**\n   - **UPSC Civil Services Exam (IAS/IPS/IFS, etc.):** Your banking experience can be beneficial for administrative roles.\n   - **State PSC Exams:** For state-level administrative and service roles.\n\n### 3. **Central Government Jobs**\n   - **SSC (Staff Selection Commission):**\n     - Combined Graduate Level (CGL) Exam: For roles like Assistant Audit Officer, Income Tax Inspector, etc.\n     - Combined Higher Secondary Level (CHSL) Exam: For clerical and assistant roles.\n   - **Ministry of Finance:**\n     - Junior Accounts Officer, Tax Assistant, and other finance-related roles.\n   - **Railway Jobs:**\n     - RRB NTPC (Non-Technical Popular Categories): For roles like Commercial Apprentice, Traffic Apprentice, etc.\n\n### 4. **Public Sector Undertakings (PSUs)**\n   - **Banking and Financial PSUs:** Like SIDBI, EXIM Bank, etc.\n   - **Other PSUs:** Like Oil and Gas, Power, etc., which often require finance and administrative professionals.\n\n### 5. **Insurance Sector**\n   - **LIC (Life Insurance Corporation of India):**\n     - AAO (Assistant Administrative Officer): For managerial roles.\n     - ADO (Apprentice Development Officer): For sales and development roles.\n   - **GIC (General Insurance Corporation of India):**\n     - Officers in various departments.\n\n### 6. **Defence Services**\n   - **Indian Army/Navy/Air Force:** Through entries like Short Service Commission (SSC) for graduates.\n\n### 7. **State Government Jobs**\n   - **State Bank Jobs:** For clerical and officer roles.\n   - **State Finance Departments:** For roles like Accountant, Auditor, etc.\n   - **State Public Service Commission Exams:** For various state-level administrative and service roles.\n\n### 8. **Other Roles**\n   - **NIC (National Informatics Centre):** For IT and finance roles.\n   - **Indian Statistical Service (ISS):** For statistical and data analysis roles.\n\n### Steps to Apply:\n1. **Identify the Exams:** Research the exams required for the roles you are interested in.\n2. **Prepare:** Focus on the syllabus and previous years' question papers.\n3. **Apply Online:** Keep an eye on official notifications and apply within the deadlines.\n4. **Stay Updated:** Regularly check official websites like UPSC, SSC, IBPS, etc., for new job notifications.\n\n### Key Websites:\n- **UPSC:** [UPSC Official Website](https://www.upsc.gov.in)\n- **SSC:** [SSC Official Website](https://ssc.nic.in)\n- **IBPS:** [IBPS Official Website](https://www.ibps.in)\n- **RBI:** [RBI Official Website](https://www.rbi.org.in)\n- **NABARD:** [NABARD Official Website](https://www.nabard.org)\n\n### Conclusion:\nYour banking experience can give you a competitive edge in various government roles, especially those related to finance, administration, and regulatory functions. Prepare systematically and apply for the exams that align with your career goals.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
